<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec61-InnerProduct" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Inner Product, Length, and Orthogonality</title>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-Length">
    <title>Length of a Vector</title>
    
    <p>
      The <term>length</term> of a vector, (aka the <term>magnitude</term> or the <term>norm</term>), can be computed using the Pythagorean Theorem (in <m>\R^2</m> or <m>\R^3</m> for possible visualization). 
    </p>

    <definition xml:id="def-Length">
      <title>Length of a Vector</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>\v{v} = \begin{bmatrix} v_1 \\ v_2 \\ \vdots \\ v_n \end{bmatrix}\in \R^n</m>. 
          Its <term>length</term>, denoted <m>\|\v{v}\|</m>, is
          <md>
            \|\v{v}\| = \sqrt{v_1^2 + v_2^2 + \cdots v_n^2}
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <p>
      Using this formula, we can define the <em>distance</em> between two vectors, which is essentially the difference between the tip of two vectors. 
    </p>

    <definition xml:id="def-DistanceVector">
      <title>Distance between two Vectors</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>\v{v}, \v{w} \in \R^n</m> such that <m>\v{v} = \begin{bmatrix} v_1 \\ v_2 \\ \vdots \\ v_n \end{bmatrix}</m> and <m>\v{w} = \begin{bmatrix} w_1 \\ w_2 \\ \vdots \\ w_n \end{bmatrix}</m>. 
          The <term>distance</term> between them, denoted <m>\dist(\v{v}, \v{w})</m>, is
          <md>
            \dist(\v{v}, \v{w}) = \sqrt{\lp v_1 - w_1 \rp^2 + \lp v_2 - w_2 \rp^2 + \cdots + \lp v_n - w_n \rp^2}
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-InnerProduct">
    <title>Inner Product</title>
    
    <p>
      You may recall that you learned the concept called the <term>inner product</term> before. 
    </p>

    <definition xml:id="def-InnerProduct">
      <title>Inner Product</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          The <term>inner product</term> <m>\boldsymbol{\v{v}, \v{w}}</m> of two vectors
          <md>
            \v{v} = \begin{bmatrix} v_1 \\ v_2 \\ \vdots v_n \end{bmatrix} \, , \qquad \v{w} = \begin{bmatrix} w_1 \\ w_2 \\ \vdots w_n \end{bmatrix}
          </md>
          is the scalar defined by
          <md>
            \v{v}, \v{w} = v_1 w_1 + v_2 w_2 + \cdots + v_n w_n
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

      <p>
        Let <m>\v{v}, \v{w} \in \R^n</m> be two vectors defined as 
        <md>
          \v{v} = \begin{pmatrix} v_1 \\ v_2 \\ \vdots \\ v_n \end{pmatrix} 
          \, , \qquad 
          \v{w} = \begin{pmatrix} w_1 \\ w_2 \\ \vdots \\ w_n \end{pmatrix}
        </md>
        Then the standard inner product of <m>\v{v}</m> and <m>\v{w}</m> , denoted by <m>\v{v}, \v{w} </m>, is defined as
        <md>
          \v{v}, \v{w}  = \v{v}^T \v{w} = \begin{pmatrix} v_1 \amp v_2 \amp \cdots \amp v_n \end{pmatrix} \begin{pmatrix} w_1 \\ w_2 \\ \vdots \\ w_n \end{pmatrix} = v_1 w_1 + v_2 w_2 + \cdots + v_n w_n
        </md>
      </p>

    <p>
      Observe that we can find the inner product of two vectors by <em>multiplying their corresponding components and adding the results</em>.
    </p>

    <example>
      <p>
        Compute the following inner products: 
        <ol marker="a.">
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 2 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}, \begin{bmatrix} 4 \\ 3 \\ 5 \end{bmatrix} </m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\begin{bmatrix} -3 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}, \begin{bmatrix} 4 \\ 6 \end{bmatrix} </m>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>

      <solution>
        <p>
          <ol marker="a.">
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 2 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}\cdot \begin{bmatrix} 4 \\ 3 \\ 5 \end{bmatrix} = 1\cdot 4 + 2\cdot 3 + 1\cdot 5 = 4 + 6 + 5 = 15</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\begin{bmatrix} -3 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}\cdot \begin{bmatrix} 4 \\ 6 \end{bmatrix} = -3\cdot 4 + 1\cdot 6 = -12 + 6 = -6</m>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <p>
      Remember that the inner product of two vectors results in a <em>scalar</em> (a real number) and not another vector. 
      The inner product has several useful properties that we summarize in the following theorem.
    </p>

    <theorem xml:id="thm-InnerProductProperties">
      <title>Properties of the Inner Product</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <ol marker="i.">
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\v{0}\cdot \v{v} = 0</m>, where <m>\v{0}</m> is the zero vector. 
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <term>Commutativity: </term> <m>\v{v}\cdot \v{w} = \v{w} \cdot \v{v}</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <term>Pulling out scalars: </term> <m>(\lambda \v{v}) \cdot \v{w} = \v{v}, xxzx``\lambda \v{w} = \lambda \v{v}\cdot \v{w}</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <term>Distributive Law: </term> <m>\v{u}\cdot \v{v} + \v{w} = \v{u}\cdot \v{v} + \v{u}\cdot \v{w} </m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <term>Relation with length: </term> <m>\v{v}, \v{v} = \|\v{v}\|^2</m>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>
    
    <proof>
      <title>Proof(ish) of the above theorem</title>
      <p>
        The proofs of the properties are pretty straightforward using the definition of the inner product. 
        Richard will prove some of them in <m>\R^3</m> and leave the rest as exercises for you to verify (especially if you are thinking about majoring in math). 
        You may also want to see if you are convinced that Richard's proofs can be generalized to <m>\R^n</m>. 
      </p>

      <p>
        <ol marker="i.">
          <li>
            <p>
              Let <m>\v{v} = \begin{bmatrix} v_1 \\ v_2 \\ v_3 \end{bmatrix}</m>. 
              Then
              <md>
                \v{0}, \v{v} = 0 \cdot v_1 + 0 \cdot v_2 + 0 \cdot v_3 = 0
              </md>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Let <m>\v{v} = \begin{bmatrix} v_1 \\ v_2 \\ v_3 \end{bmatrix}</m> and <m>\v{w} = \begin{bmatrix} w_1 \\ w_2 \\ w_3 \end{bmatrix}</m>. 
              Then
              <md>
                <mrow> \v{v}, \v{w} \amp= v_1 w_1 + v_2 w_2 + v_3 w_3 </mrow>
                <mrow> \amp= w_1 v_1 + w_2 v_2 + w_3 v_3 </mrow>
                <mrow> \amp= \v{w}, \v{v} </mrow>
              </md>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              The proof is left as an exercise for the reader. 
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              The proof is left as an exercise for the reader.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Let <m>\v{v} = \begin{bmatrix} v_1 \\ v_2 \\ v_3 \end{bmatrix}</m>. 
              Then
              <md>
                \v{v}, \v{v} = v_1^2 + v_2^2 + v_3^2 = \|\v{v}\|^2
              </md>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </proof>

    <p>
      Using these properties, we can prove some cool results! 
      For example, do you know that the sum of the squares of the lengths of the four sides of a parallelogram is equal to the sum of the squares of the lengths of its two diagonals? 
      This is also known as the <term>parallelogram law</term>. 
    </p>

    <theorem xml:id="thm-ParallelogramLaw">
      <title>Parallelogram Law</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <md>
            \|\v{u} + \v{v}\|^2 + \|\v{u} - \v{v}\|^2 = 2\|\v{u}\|^2 + 2\|\v{v}\|^2
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>
    
    <example>
      <p>
        Prove the parallelogram law using the properties of the inner product. 
        The diagram below shows a parallelogram formed by the vectors <m>\v{u}</m> and <m>\v{v}</m>. 
      </p>

      <figure>
        <image source="sec123-ParallelogramLaw-Diagram.png" width="65%"></image>
        <caption>Parallelogram formed by vectors <m>\v{u}</m> and <m>\v{v}</m></caption>
      </figure>

      <hint>
        <p>
          The parallelogram has two diagonals with the lengths of <m>\|\v{u} + \v{v}\|</m> and <m>\|\v{u} - \v{v}\|</m>. 
          Also, the sides have lengths of <m>\|\v{u}\|</m> and <m>\|\v{v}\|</m>, respectively. 
        </p>

        <p>
          We are learning about the inner product so let's get some inner products involved!
          One of the inner product properties states that <m>\|\v{v}\|^2 = \v{v}, \v{v}</m> so converting all the lengths into inner products is a good start! 
        </p>
      </hint>

      <solution>
        <p>
          <md>
            <mrow> \|\v{u} + \v{v}\|^2 + \|\v{u} - \v{v}\|^2 \amp= \v{u} + \v{v}, \v{u} + \v{v} + \la \v{u} - \v{v}, \v{u} - \v{v} </mrow>
            <mrow> \amp= \v{u}, \v{u} + 2 \v{u}, \v{v} + \v{v}, \v{v} + \v{u}, \v{u} - 2\v{u}, \v{v} + \v{v}, \v{v}</mrow>
            <mrow> \amp= 2 \v{u}, \v{u} + 2 \v{v}, \v{v} </mrow>
            <mrow> \amp= 2\|\v{u}\|^2 + 2\|\v{v}\|^2 </mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <p>
      Now that we know what the inner product is and some of its properties, we will next explore why we care about it. 
    </p>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-Orthogonality-Intro">
    <title>Orthogonality</title>
    
    <p>
      Long story short, two vectors are <term>orthogonal</term> if their inner product is zero. 
      But what does it look like? We will explore it more in <xref ref="sec63-OrthogonalProjection"/>. 
    </p>
  </subsection>

  <worksheet xml:id="ws-sec61">
    <title>Some Exercises for This Section</title>
    
    <introduction>
      <p>
        Richard included some practice problems that cover some main concepts in this section. 
        You don't need to turn it in, but you are highly encouraged to work on this with your classmates. 
        The problems here may end up being in-class practice problems, homework problems, and/or exam problems. 
        Reach out to Richard for help if you get stuck or have any questions. 
      </p>

      <p>
        Only the final answers are included to some of the problems for you to check your result. 
        If you want to check your work, talk to Richard and he is happy to discuss the process with you. 
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <exercisegroup>
        <introduction>
            <p>Compute the quantities the following exercises using the vectors 
            <me>u=\begin{bmatrix}-1\\ 2\end{bmatrix}, \quad v=\begin{bmatrix}2\\ 3\end{bmatrix}, \quad w=\begin{bmatrix}3\\ -1\\ -5\end{bmatrix}, \quad x=\begin{bmatrix}6\\ -2\\ 3\end{bmatrix}</me>
            </p>
        </introduction>
        
        <exercise number="6.1.3">
            <statement>
                <me>\frac{1}{w\cdot w}w</me>
            </statement>
        </exercise>

        <exercise number="6.1.5">
            <statement>
                <me>\left(\frac{u\cdot v}{v\cdot v}\right)v</me>
            </statement>
        </exercise>
    </exercisegroup>

    <exercisegroup>
        <introduction>
            <p>In the following exercise, find a unit vector in the direction of the given vector.</p>
        </introduction>

        <exercise number="6.1.9">
            <statement>
                <me>\begin{bmatrix}-30\\ 40\end{bmatrix}</me>
            </statement>
        </exercise>

        <exercise number="6.1.11">
            <statement>
                <me>\begin{bmatrix}\frac{7}{4}\\ \frac{1}{2}\\ 1\end{bmatrix}</me>
            </statement>
        </exercise>
    </exercisegroup>

    <exercise number="6.1.13">
        <statement>
            <p>Find the distance between <m>x=\begin{bmatrix}10\\ -3\end{bmatrix}</m> and <m>y=\begin{bmatrix}-1\\ -5\end{bmatrix}</m>.</p>
        </statement>
    </exercise>

        <exercise number="6.1.17">
            <statement>
              <p>  
                Determine if the following pair of vectors is orthogonal. 
              <me>u=\begin{bmatrix}3\\ 2\\ -5\\ 0\end{bmatrix}, \quad v=\begin{bmatrix}-4\\ 1\\ -2\\ 6\end{bmatrix}</me>
              </p>
            </statement>
        </exercise>

    <exercisegroup>
        <introduction>
            <p>In Exercises 19-27, all vectors are in <m>\mathbb{R}^{n}</m>. Mark each statement True or False (T/F). Justify each answer.</p>
        </introduction>

        <exercise number="6.1.19">
            <statement>
                <p>(T/F) <m>v\cdot v=||v||^{2}</m></p>
            </statement>
        </exercise>

        <exercise number="6.1.21">
            <statement>
                <p>(T/F) If the distance from <m>u</m> to <m>v</m> equals the distance from <m>u</m> to <m>-v</m>, then <m>u</m> and <m>v</m> are orthogonal.</p>
            </statement>
        </exercise>

        <exercise number="6.1.23">
            <statement>
                <p>(T/F) If vectors <m>v_{1},...,v_{p}</m> span a subspace <m>W</m> and if <m>x</m> is orthogonal to each <m>v_{j}</m> for <m>j=1,...,p</m> then <m>x</m> is in <m>W^{\perp}</m>.</p>
            </statement>
        </exercise>

        <exercise number="6.1.25">
            <statement>
                <p>(T/F) For any scalar <m>c</m>, <m>||cv||=c||v||</m>.</p>
            </statement>
        </exercise>

        <exercise number="6.1.27">
            <statement>
                <p>(T/F) For a square matrix <m>A</m>, vectors in Col <m>A</m> are orthogonal to vectors in Nul <m>A</m>.</p>
            </statement>
        </exercise>
    </exercisegroup>

  </worksheet>

</section>